</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/ukaledan.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kaledan</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/26/02 5:09:43 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23443.topic&index=60>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Equipment Decay, Good or Bad?</span><hr size=1> Its pretty clear that most of the people in favour of item decay basically want/expect other peoples items to decay, but not theirs. <br>
<br>
A much better way to actually deal with the item deflation issues, provide a role for smiths, and be reasonably realistic is to require each player that wants to wear or use armour or weapons to have it be fitted for them.<br>
<br>
If you think about it, it's pretty silly to loot armour worn by an ogre and immediately wear it, it would need to be practically remade.<br>
<br>
Adjusting an item to fit its first owner would be simple and cheap. Readusting armour to fit someone else would be tricky and expensive, and would always have a chance to degrade the quality of the item. This provides the item sink, in that second hand gear can't get arbitrarily cheap, and will eventually get worn out or sold to an NPC instead of a player. However, as long as you keep an item, it would never wear out, and there would be no tedious item repair process to go through every day. <br>
<br>
With this, there is no need to have NO DROP items, you just have items that are incredibly difficult to readjust to fit anyone other than the first person to wear them.<br>
<br>
