<br>
Everyone who has said that they want the supposed economic benifits of item decay (i.e. no inflation, so you can still sell your loot for the same price at which you bought it), but also wants a mechanism whereby items can be maintained, repaired, or whatever, that means that it is always possible to avoid having anything actually decay. <br>
<br>
The only way that makes sense is if you assume everyone else is not bothering to maintain their gear, so it decays, but due to your superior intellingence and skill at clicking a button every few hours, your gear is still good as new and so can be sold for full price.<br>
<br>
Soru <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/udraxusmt.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Draxus MT</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/26/02 10:59:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23443.topic&index=66>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Equipment Decay, Good or Bad?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  God forbid they improve the game. We must protect our right to uber gear at all costs.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Did you even read my original post?  Maybe you would like to explain why you oppose gear based progression at 60 or whatever the highest level you can reach is.  How would you suggest ppl progress in the game post level cap?  AAXP?  If not for item progression post 60, I would have quit the game long ago.<br>
<br>
Someone made a very good point earlier.  Item progression promotes social interaction (guilds &amp; raids required to advance - also, the entire group must advance in order for any individual to advance).  XP progression weather by level or specialization/aaxp is group focused (assuming you can’t solo), and does nothing to encourage long term social friendships and cooperation.<br>
<br>
Lastly, the characterization of a loot whore mentality reeks of bitter jealousy coming from a person who likely cannot master the basic social skills required to work with others &amp; attain the same gear as the ppl they try to flame.<br>
<br>
